postcontent:
BRAND NEW NEVER FIRED

Blackhole Weaponry Barrels employ the use of 416R, match grade stainless steel. BHW Barrels specialize in Polygonal rifling; The shape of the lands and grooves are based on a circle, so there are no sharp corners or edges for the bullet to conform into. This means there is a tight seal and thus less bullet deformation. This rifling form is unique in its ability to allow the bullet to be centered and fully supported by the barrel’s bore.This arc shaped rifling has long been held in very high regard for its accuracy, increased velocity, reduced gas cutting and ease of cleaning.

title: For Sale:  1,000 yard Rifle
postcontent:
Savage 116 FSAK “Weather Warrior” 
.300 Remington Ultra Mag Rifle.

This incredible rifle easily pushes a 180 grain bullet out to 1,000 yards and beyond at an astonishing 3270 feet per second. It hits what you want to hit with no fuss or trouble.

$1,450 with scope
$1,100 without scope

This rifle comes with the following:

•	26” stainless steel heavy fluted barrel 
•	Custom Muzzle Brake (threaded, not pinned)
•	“Rifle Basix” adjustable trigger set at a smooth and crisp 3.5 lbs.
•	Bushnell Elite 4200 6x-24x mil dot long distance rifle scope
•	Butler Creek Flip-Up Scope Covers 
•	Choate “Ultimate Sniper” adjustable synthetic target stock
•	82 rounds Remington Premier 300 Ultra Mag ammunition. This is full power (PL3) ammo using 180 grain Swift Scirocco bullets 
•	Ballisticard Systems Ballistic Solutions Card with range data
•	Less than 200 rounds fired. 


If you bought the rifle and all these components today, it would cost you nearly $2100. 

Compare this lightly used rifle to the cost of buying new today: 

Savage (or Remington) 300 Ultra Mag Rifle		$800($1200)
Bushnell Elite 4200 6x-24x Mil Dot Scope 			$500
Butler Creek Quick Flip Scope Covers (pair)  			  $15
Choate “Ultimate Sniper” Adjustable Stock			$190
Threaded Muzzle Brake (including gunsmithing)		$175
82 rounds Remington 300 RUM ammo	 			$246
Rifle Basix Adjustable Trigger 					$150

Today’s Total								$2076


The story behind this rifle

My favorite precision rifle, a Remington 700 in .308 caliber, was very accurate out to 700 yards. Ballistically, it was capable of hitting targets at 1,000 yards, but it was awfully tricky as the .308 starts to lose steam past 800 yards. It is not the .308’s forte. 

I started looking for a rifle that could punch out to 1,000 yards without a lot of trouble. Savage rifles were well known for superb “out-of the box” accuracy, and the relatively new 300 RUM cartridge had a great reputation as a strong, long distance round, so I purchased this rifle in that caliber and modified it into a dedicated 1,000 yard rifle. The heavy stock and the muzzle brake tame the famous recoil of the 300 Ultra Mag cartridge. 

I have been very happy with the performance of this rifle, but unfortunately, the cost of ammo has tripled since I bought it, and I no longer have the desire to shoot it. I do not reload, nor do I have any desire to take up that hobby, so I made the decision to part with it. 

If you are a reloader, this would be affordable for you to shoot. 

If you want to hit a target 1,000 yards and beyond predictably and with ease, then this is the rifle for you. 

Watch this video of some guys shooting a 300 RUM out to 1300 yards:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DHyseyMeQd8

Heckler & Koch Model: USP Caliber: 40 S&W Action: Double / Single Action / 3- Mags

All major metal components on the USP are corrosion-resistant. Outside metal surfaces are protected by H&K’s proprietary “hostile environment” nitride finish. Internal metal parts are coated with a Dow Corning anti-corrosion chemical to reduce friction and wear.

 The gunmaker tested the MK23′s recoil system with over 30k rounds of +P ammunition followed by 6k high pressure proof rounds. After disassembling the gun the Germans found no damage or excessive wear to any of the components.

 And then they did some more tests . . .

 The ballistic boffins froze the USP to −42 °C (−43.5 °F), fired it and then frozen it again. They heated it to 67 °C (152.6 °F) and fired it. They cycled between these extremes several times. They subjected USP to standard NATO mud and rain abuse. They immersed it in water and sprayed it with sea water. They dropped it from six feet, hammer first, onto a steel-backed concrete slab.

 H&K employees deliberately lodged a bullet in the barrel and then sent another one down the pipe. The second bullet cleared the obstruction producing only a minor bulge in the barrel. They loaded a full magazine and then fired the gun again with the bulging barrel. The resulting group measured less than 4 inches of deviation at 25 meters – a standard that some new guns would be lucky to hold.
